= pam_fnal_vncpasswd(8)

== Name

pam_fnal_vncpasswd - PAM module for per-user VNC password authentication

== Synopsis

----
pam_fnal_vncpasswd.so [debug]
----

== Description

*pam_fnal_vncpasswd* authenticates a user against a per-user VNC password file
managed by *@PROJECT_NAME@*(1).  It is designed to run exclusively inside a
single-user VNC session process (for example, *neatvnc* under *weston*) that
runs as the session owner.

The module reads a *crypt*(3) hash stored in
*~/@VNC_PASSWD_DIR@/@VNC_PASSWD_FILENAME@*, verifies the supplied password
using a constant-time comparison, and zeroes all sensitive buffers before
returning.

=== Session Binding

Because the VNC session process runs as the authenticated user, this module
compares the UID resolved from the supplied username against *getuid*(2) of
the calling process.  A mismatch causes *PAM_AUTH_ERR* before any password
file is opened.

*This module must not be deployed in multi-user PAM services* (such as *sshd*
or *login*) where the process runs as root.  In that context *getuid*(2)
returns 0 and the binding check would reject every non-root user.

=== Password File Validation

The password file is opened with *O_NOFOLLOW | O_NONBLOCK* to prevent
symlink-swap and FIFO blocking attacks.  After opening, *fstat*(2) verifies:

* The file is a regular file.
* The file is owned by the session user.
* No executable or group/world read-write bits are set.

=== Authentication Sequence

. Resolve the home directory via *getpwnam_r*(3).
. Reject if the resolved UID does not equal *getuid*(2).
. Construct the canonical password file path.
. Open and validate the password file (TOCTOU-safe).
. Read the stored hash.
. Verify the supplied password using a constant-time comparison
  (*CRYPTO_memcmp* or *gnutls_memcmp* depending on build configuration).
. Call *explicit_bzero*(3) on all sensitive buffers.

== Options

*debug*::
  Emit non-sensitive decision-point messages to *syslog*(3) at *LOG_DEBUG*.
  Passwords, hashes, and raw file contents are never logged.

== PAM Stack Configuration

=== Recommended Configuration

The following configuration authenticates with the VNC password when present
and falls back to *pam_unix*(8) when the user has no VNC password file:

----
# /etc/pam.d/your-vnc-service
auth [success=done authinfo_unavail=ignore default=die] \
    pam_fnal_vncpasswd.so
auth sufficient pam_unix.so
----

The bracket syntax is required because *sufficient* treats
*PAM_AUTHINFO_UNAVAIL* as failure and will not fall through to *pam_unix*.

*authinfo_unavail=ignore*;;
  Skip to the next module when the user has no VNC password file.
*success=done*;;
  Short-circuit the stack on successful VNC authentication.
*default=die*;;
  Terminate the stack on any other failure, including *PAM_AUTH_ERR* and
  *PAM_USER_UNKNOWN*.  This prevents an attacker from deliberately triggering
  an error to bypass a VNC password that is present.

=== Debug Configuration

----
auth [success=done authinfo_unavail=ignore default=die] \
    pam_fnal_vncpasswd.so debug
auth sufficient pam_unix.so
----

== Return Values

*PAM_SUCCESS*::
  The supplied password matches the stored hash.

*PAM_AUTH_ERR*::
  Authentication failed: session binding check failed, or the supplied
  password does not match the stored hash.

*PAM_USER_UNKNOWN*::
  The username was not found in the system password database, or the passwd
  entry has no valid home directory.

*PAM_AUTHINFO_UNAVAIL*::
  The password file could not be opened or validated, or the stored hash
  could not be read.  The *authinfo_unavail=ignore* action in the PAM stack
  configuration is intended to handle this case.

*PAM_PERM_DENIED*::
  Returned by *pam_sm_chauthtok*(3) — password changes via PAM are not
  supported.  Use *@PROJECT_NAME@*(1) instead.

*PAM_SERVICE_ERR*::
  Returned by *pam_sm_acct_mgmt*(3), *pam_sm_open_session*(3), and
  *pam_sm_close_session*(3) — this module implements only password
  authentication.

*PAM_IGNORE*::
  Returned by *pam_sm_setcred*(3) — this module manages no credentials.

== Password File

----
~/@VNC_PASSWD_DIR@/@VNC_PASSWD_FILENAME@
----

A single line containing a *crypt*(3) hash produced by *@PROJECT_NAME@*(1).
The file must be owned by the user, not a symlink, and have permissions
*0600* (no execute, no group or world access).

Use *@PROJECT_NAME@*(1) to create and update this file.

== Files

*~/@VNC_PASSWD_DIR@/@VNC_PASSWD_FILENAME@*::
  Per-user VNC password file.

== Notes

The *pam_sm_chauthtok*, *pam_sm_acct_mgmt*, *pam_sm_open_session*, and
*pam_sm_close_session* entry points exist because Linux-PAM resolves all six
*pam_sm_** symbols at *dlopen*(3) time.  A missing symbol breaks the entire
auth stack regardless of which service types appear in the PAM configuration.

